An empty position created a fancyhead element which looked like this:
```
\fancyhead[]{
}
```
but this works just as well:
```
\fancyhead{
}
```

I tried some basic implementations using `walk` and `iter_child_nodes`. Like:
```python
def return_node_after_return(tree):
    """
    Iterate over list of every node present in each level of the ast.
    Return the item just after return statement.
    """
    for parent_node in ast.walk(tree):
        child_nodes = [child_node for child_node in ast.iter_child_nodes(parent_node)]
        for i, node in enumerate(child_nodes):
            if isinstance(node, ast.Return):
                try:
                    return child_nodes[i+1]
                except IndexError:
                    return None
```
But, lies a pitfall: The _if-else_, _try-except_ clauses are a single node. Thus it would be more difficult to list items in the 'same logical level'. This is also sub-optimal performance wise, but I guess, we can improve it.

Is the current approach not feasible?

For backward copatibility, I would prefer to see:

```python
def __init__(self, for_user=None):
   if for_user is None:
       for_user = AnonymousUser()
```

@dimberman Ah, okay. Makes sense for the development.

Regarding the image size, I'm pretty sure that the size will stay roughly the same. Right now all the dependencies are in the cached layer, otherwise they will be in the lower layer. Either way, the dependencies have to go in the image.
I would even argue that the image will be bigger in this case, since we are checking once more if all the dependencies are there at the `pip install` below.

